		<a name="top" id="top"></a>
		<div id="siteNotice"><script type='text/javascript'>if (wgNotice != '') document.writeln(wgNotice);</script></div>		<h1 id="firstHeading" class="firstHeading">New world order</h1>
		<div id="bodyContent">
			<h3 id="siteSub">From Wikipedia, the free encyclopedia</h3>
			<div id="contentSub"></div>
									<div id="jump-to-nav">Jump to: <a href="#column-one">navigation</a>, <a href="#searchInput">search</a></div>			<!-- start content -->
			<div class="dablink">For other uses, see disambiguation pages for <a href="/wiki/New_World_Order" title="New World Order">New World Order</a> and <a href="/wiki/NWO" title="NWO">NWO</a>.</div>
<div class="dablink">For the conspiracy theory see , see <a href="/wiki/New_World_Order_(conspiracy_theory)" title="New World Order (conspiracy theory)">New World Order (conspiracy theory)</a>.</div>
<p>The term "<b>new world order</b>" has been used to refer to a new period of history evidencing a dramatic change in world political thought and the <a href="/wiki/Balance_of_power_in_international_relations" title="Balance of power in international relations">balance of power</a>. Despite various interpretations of this political philosophy, it has often been represented by the idea of a single World Government. The first Western usages of the term surrounded <a href="/wiki/Woodrow_Wilson" title="Woodrow Wilson">Woodrow Wilson</a>'s <a href="/wiki/Fourteen_Points" title="Fourteen Points">Fourteen Points</a> and call for a <a href="/wiki/League_of_Nations" title="League of Nations">League of Nations</a> following the devastation of <a href="/wiki/World_War_I" title="World War I">World War I</a>. The phrase was used sparingly at the end of the <a href="/wiki/Second_World_War" title="Second World War" class="mw-redirect">Second World War</a> when describing the plans for the <a href="/wiki/United_Nations" title="United Nations">United Nations</a> and <a href="/wiki/Bretton_Woods_system" title="Bretton Woods system">Bretton Woods system</a>, in part because of the negative association to the failed League of Nations the phrase would bring. In retrospect however, many commentators have applied the term retroactively to the order put in place by the <a href="/wiki/Allies_of_World_War_II" title="Allies of World War II">WWII victors</a> as a "new world order."</p>
<p>The most widely discussed application of the phrase of recent times came at the end of the <a href="/wiki/Cold_War" title="Cold War">Cold War</a>. Presidents <a href="/wiki/Mikhail_Gorbachev" title="Mikhail Gorbachev">Mikhail Gorbachev</a> and <a href="/wiki/George_H.W._Bush" title="George H.W. Bush" class="mw-redirect">George H.W. Bush</a> used the term to try to define the nature of the post <a href="/wiki/Cold_War" title="Cold War">Cold War</a> era, and the spirit of <a href="/wiki/Great_power" title="Great power">great power</a> cooperation that they hoped might materialize. Gorbachev's initial formulation was wide ranging and <a href="/wiki/Idealism_(international_relations)" title="Idealism (international relations)">idealistic</a>, but his ability to press for it was severely limited by the <a href="/wiki/History_of_the_Soviet_Union_(1985-1991)" title="History of the Soviet Union (1985-1991)" class="mw-redirect">internal crisis of the Soviet system</a>. Bush's vision was, in comparison, much more circumscribed and <a href="/wiki/Pragmatism" title="Pragmatism">pragmatic</a>, perhaps even instrumental at times, and closely linked to the <a href="/wiki/Gulf_War" title="Gulf War">Gulf War</a>.</p>
